{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "foot_3 However, such repeated retraining is expensive and so more efficient pointwise influence analysis methods were studied.",
    "Different assumptions about the training data distribution lead to different definitions of the most likely outlier.",
    "For example, Srikantan (1961), Snedecor & Cochran (1968), and Ellenberg (1976) all assume that training data outliers arise from mean shifts in normally distributed training data.",
    "Under this constraint, their methods all identify the maximum likelihood outlier as the training instance with the largest absolute residual, |y i - * ⊺ x i |.",
    "However, Cook & Weisberg (1982) prove that under different distributional assumptions (e.g., a variance shift instead of a mean shift), the maximum likelihood outlier may not have the largest residual."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "For example, Srikantan (1961), Snedecor & Cochran (1968), and Ellenberg (1976) all assume that training data outliers arise from mean shifts in normally distributed training data.",
    "However, Cook & Weisberg (1982) prove that under different distributional assumptions (e.g., a variance shift instead of a mean shift), the maximum likelihood outlier may not have the largest residual."
  ]
}